==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stoic
<hw>Sto"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>stoicus</ets>,
Gr. <?/, fr. <?/, adj., literally, of or pertaining to a colonnade, from
<?/ a roofed colonnade, a porch, especially, a porch in Athens where
Zeno and his successors taught.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A disciple of
the philosopher Zeno; one of a Greek sect which held that men should be
free from passion, unmoved by joy or grief, and should submit without
complaint to unavoidable necessity, by which all things are
governed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a person not easily excited; an apathetic
person; one who is apparently or professedly indifferent to pleasure or
pain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>Stoic</qex> of the woods, a man without a tear.</q>
<rj><qau>Campbell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>School of Stoics</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>The
Porch</cref>, under <er>Porch</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stoical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Stoic</ent>⟦br⟧
